Covid La

Read in Data

The covid data comes from the NYT. Its county level data.

#covid <- read_csv("us-counties.csv")
covid <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/master/us-counties.csv")

Lets look at it.

covid

Id like to filter the data by just LA county and plot it using a bar chart.

covid %>% 
  filter(county == "Los Angeles") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = deaths)) + 
  geom_col() +
  cowplot::theme_minimal_vgrid(16) +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(), 
        legend.position = "none") +
  xlab("number of covid-19 deaths in LA")

Lets use the same filter and then make a line graph.

covid %>% 
  filter(county == "Los Angeles") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = deaths)) + geom_line() +
  cowplot::theme_minimal_vgrid(16) +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(), 
        legend.position = "none") +
  xlab("number of covid-19 deaths in LA")

Some more filtering. Here I want to pull out hotspot countys, Orleans, LA, NYC, and King county. The problem is that there are more than one Orleans counties (parish), so I want to first filter out the other Orleans counties in NY and Vermont then do our county filter. Well then pipe the result into ggplot and create a facet (small multiples) of those counties deaths by covid.

covid_grp <- covid %>% 
  group_by(county, state) %>% 
  arrange(date) %>% 
  filter(!(county=='Orleans' & (state=='New York' | state=="Vermont"))) %>% 
  filter(county %in% c("Orleans", "Los Angeles", "New York City", "King") & state %in% c("Louisiana", "California", "Washington", "New York")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = deaths, color = county)) + geom_line() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "YlOrRd") +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(), 
        legend.position = "none") +
  cowplot::theme_minimal_grid(12) +
  facet_wrap(~county, ncol = 2)

covid_grp

Lets calculate a rate of growth. Here lets use the death rate b/c testing is still limited and death rate serves as more of a measure of how our stay at home efforts are doing. Using mutate, well use the lag function to create a diff_growth column that is the number of deaths that occured since the previous day. This because the NYT data gives us cumulative deaths, not the number that occured each day. Well then create a rate_percent column that takes the diff_growth and divides by the diff_date (one since this is daily data) and then by the number of cumulative deaths on that day times 100. So, this number is the rate of growth from the previous day.

covid_day_diff_rate <- covid %>% 
  group_by(county, state) %>% 
  arrange(date) %>% 
  mutate(diff_date = date - lag(date),  # Difference in time (just in case there are gaps)
         diff_growth = deaths - lag(deaths), # Difference in deaths between days
         rate_percent = (diff_growth / as.double(diff_date)) / deaths * 100)  # growth rate in percent

Now I want to see this rate expressed by week. Lubridate has a nice function that will return the epiweek epidemological week number used by WHO and CDC. I group_by that epiweek and then take the mean of the daily means to give us a weekly mean. Ill save as a new dataframe so I can work with it.

covid_drate_byweek <- covid_day_diff_rate %>% 
  select(date, county, state, deaths, diff_growth, rate_percent) %>% 
  group_by(week = epiweek(date), county, state) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  summarize(num_deaths = sum(diff_growth), week_avg_increase = mean(rate_percent))
